    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-07-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-07-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="1540"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1540">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/71.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">French Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Translation.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">French Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Manchester</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-07-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 23, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: I have the honor to
                    communicate herewith to your excellency a report from the French Consular Agent
                    at El Paso, giving an accurate account of the experiences of the Christian
                    Brothers of the Zacatecas school.<note n="144" xml:id="d1540fn144">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Contrary to what was at first reported, the responsibility for the murder of
                    Brothers Astru and Gilles seems to lie with General Tomas Urbina, and, for the
                    ill treatment undergone by the other fourteen Brothers, with General Manuel
                    Chao.</p>
                <pb facs="0989" n="873" xml:id="pg_873"/>
                <p>It seems that General Villa was not apprized of the facts until later and that he
                    even gave the prisoners a safe conduct.</p>
                <p>Be pleased to accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">R. Clausse</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
